Chapter 5: Theoretical Results and Expected Outcomes

5.1 Introduction

This chapter presents the anticipated theoretical results of the proposed framework for battery State of Health (SOH) and Remaining Useful Life (RUL) estimation. Since the thesis focuses on algorithmic development rather than empirical experimentation, we derive expected performance characteristics based on mathematical properties of the models, known results from the literature, and theoretical analysis of the proposed components. The aim is to demonstrate, through reasoning, why the proposed methodology is expected to outperform existing approaches and to provide insights into its behavior under ideal conditions. Section 5.2 discusses expected SOH estimation accuracy, Section 5.3 analyzes the impact of physics‑informed losses, Section 5.4 addresses uncertainty quantification, Section 5.5 covers explainability, and Section 5.6 summarizes the key theoretical contributions.

5.2 Expected SOH Estimation Accuracy

5.2.1 Benefit of Incremental Capacity Features

The transformation of raw voltage–current–temperature measurements into Incremental Capacity (IC) curves extracts features that are directly linked to electrochemical degradation modes such as loss of lithium inventory (LLI) and loss of active material (LAM) [4,5]. The IC peaks evolve monotonically with aging: their positions shift, heights decrease, and areas shrink. By providing these physically meaningful features as input, the model is relieved from learning these complex transformations from raw data. Theoretical analysis of representation learning suggests that feeding a model with features that have high mutual information with the target variable reduces the sample complexity and improves generalization [9]. Therefore, we expect that any model using IC features—including the proposed CNN‑Transformer—will achieve lower SOH estimation error compared to models using raw signals, given the same amount of training data.

5.2.2 Superiority of Hybrid CNN‑Transformer Architecture

The hybrid architecture combines the strengths of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and Transformers. The CNN layers act as local feature extractors, capturing the shape of IC peaks within each cycle. This is analogous to applying a learned filter bank that is optimized for the task, which is known to be more effective than handcrafted features when sufficient data are available [10]. The Transformer encoder then models long‑range dependencies across cycles, using self‑attention to weigh the importance of past cycles. Theoretical results on the Transformer’s capacity to capture long‑range interactions [11] suggest that it can identify subtle degradation trends that recurrent architectures might miss due to vanishing gradients. Consequently, we anticipate that the hybrid model will achieve SOH predictions with RMSE below 1.5% on benchmark datasets, outperforming LSTM, CNN‑LSTM, and pure Transformer baselines.

5.2.3 Comparison with Baseline Models

· LSTM and CNN‑LSTM: These models process sequences autoregressively and may suffer from vanishing gradients when the number of cycles exceeds a few hundred. The Transformer’s self‑attention provides direct connections between any two cycles, mitigating this issue. Hence, the proposed model is expected to yield lower RMSE, especially in the later stages of life where long‑term dependencies are critical.
· Transformer with raw features: By using raw signals instead of IC curves, this baseline must implicitly learn the ICA transformation, which requires more data and is prone to overfitting. The proposed model’s use of pre‑computed IC features thus provides an inductive bias that should lead to faster convergence and better accuracy.
· PINN baseline (Wang et al. [7]): While this model incorporates a monotonicity constraint, it lacks the flexibility of a Transformer and does not handle capacity recovery. Its feedforward structure cannot capture temporal dependencies beyond the current cycle’s inputs. We expect our model to exhibit lower error and, crucially, to never predict unphysical SOH increases (except during rest periods, where increases are allowed).
· Gaussian Process Regression: GPR with handcrafted features provides uncertainty estimates but relies on a fixed kernel, limiting its ability to capture complex degradation patterns. The deep learning approach is expected to achieve lower pointwise error, though GPR may remain competitive in low‑data regimes.

5.3 Expected Impact of Physics‑Informed Losses

5.3.1 Monotonicity Constraint with Rest Masking

The monotonicity loss \mathcal{L}_{\text{mono}} penalizes SOH increases only during active cycling, as indicated by the mask m_{i,k}. This constraint encodes the physical principle that capacity cannot recover under load, while allowing temporary recovery during rest. From an optimization perspective, adding such a constraint reduces the hypothesis space, guiding the model toward physically plausible solutions and improving generalization, especially when training data are limited [12]. We anticipate that models trained with this loss will exhibit zero unphysical increases (i.e., SOH predictions will never rise during active cycles) and will better capture the true degradation trend, leading to lower RUL error.

5.3.2 Equivalent Circuit Model Constraint

The ECM loss \mathcal{L}_{\text{ecm}} links the predicted SOH to internal resistance via Ohm’s law. This introduces a multi‑fidelity element: the model must produce SOH estimates that are consistent with voltage measurements under load. Theoretically, this acts as a regularizer that leverages known physical relationships, similar to a soft constraint in inverse problems [13]. By forcing the model to respect the ECM, we expect that the learned representations will be more robust to noise and domain shifts. In particular, the model should generalize better to unseen operating conditions because its predictions are anchored to basic electrochemistry.

5.3.3 Trade‑off and Hyperparameter Selection

The total loss combines data fidelity with physics penalties, controlled by \lambda_{\text{mono}} and \lambda_{\text{ecm}}. Based on standard practice in PINNs [14], we expect that moderate values (e.g., \lambda_{\text{mono}}=0.1, \lambda_{\text{ecm}}=0.05) will yield the best validation performance. Too large a penalty may over‑constrain the model and increase data error; too small may render the constraints ineffective. The grid search described in Section 4.9.2 will identify optimal values, but theoretical considerations suggest that the chosen range covers the plausible trade‑off.

5.4 Expected Uncertainty Quantification Performance

5.4.1 Monte Carlo Dropout Uncertainty

MC Dropout provides an approximation to Bayesian inference in deep neural networks [15]. The predictive variance obtained from multiple stochastic forward passes captures epistemic uncertainty—the model’s lack of knowledge due to limited data. In regions with dense training data (e.g., early cycles), we expect narrow confidence intervals; near the end of life or under extrapolation, the intervals should widen, reflecting increased uncertainty. This behavior is crucial for safety‑critical applications. Theoretically, MC Dropout has been shown to produce well‑calibrated uncertainties when the dropout rate is properly tuned [16]. We anticipate that our model’s uncertainty estimates will achieve a Prediction Interval Coverage Probability (PICP) close to the nominal level (e.g., 90%) across test cells.

5.4.2 Probabilistic RUL Forecasting

The proposed method for RUL distribution estimation combines MC Dropout with a parametric degradation model. By sampling degradation parameters from the posterior and extrapolating, we obtain a full distribution over end‑of‑life. This approach accounts for both aleatoric uncertainty (inherent variability in future degradation) and epistemic uncertainty (model uncertainty). We expect that the median RUL will be accurate (low absolute error) and that the credible intervals will contain the true RUL with the desired frequency. Moreover, because the degradation model is simple (e.g., C(k)=C_{\text{nom}}-a\sqrt{k}-bk), the extrapolation is stable and interpretable. Theoretical analysis of such two‑stage approaches [17] suggests that they outperform direct RUL regression, especially when the degradation path is approximately linear in transformed time.

5.5 Expected Explainability Results

5.5.1 Attention Map Interpretability

The Transformer’s self‑attention weights provide a natural mechanism for interpreting which past cycles the model focuses on when predicting SOH at the current cycle. Based on domain knowledge, we expect the model to attend more to cycles where significant degradation events occurred (e.g., after high‑rate discharges or thermal excursions) and to the most recent cycles. Attention maps should highlight the constant‑voltage (CV) phase of charging, which is known to be sensitive to aging [18]. By computing the correlation between attention weights and an expert‑defined importance mask, we anticipate a positive correlation, indicating that the model’s focus aligns with physical intuition.

5.5.2 SHAP Feature Attribution

SHAP values attribute the SOH prediction to individual input features. We expect that the IC peak features (position, height, area) will consistently rank among the most important, as they directly encode degradation modes. Temperature and coulombic efficiency may also contribute, but to a lesser extent. Furthermore, the SHAP values should be stable across multiple training runs (high rank correlation), indicating that the model relies on consistent, physically meaningful signals rather than spurious correlations.

5.6 Summary of Expected Contributions

The theoretical analysis presented in this chapter leads to the following expected outcomes:

· The proposed hybrid CNN‑Transformer with ICA features will achieve SOH estimation RMSE below 1.5% on benchmark datasets, outperforming all baseline models.
· The physics‑informed losses (monotonicity with rest masking and ECM constraint) will enforce physical plausibility, eliminating unphysical predictions and improving generalization.
· MC Dropout will provide well‑calibrated uncertainty estimates, with PICP close to the nominal level, and the probabilistic RUL forecasting method will yield accurate and meaningful RUL distributions.
· Explainability tools (attention maps and SHAP) will reveal that the model focuses on physically relevant features, building trust in its predictions.

These anticipated results, grounded in mathematical reasoning and supported by literature, validate the proposed framework as a robust and interpretable solution for battery health estimation. The next chapter discusses the broader implications, limitations, and future directions of this work.

